<TEXT>
scientists reported today they had found the 
approximate location of a gene that causes a crippling disease in 
as many as 20000 americans 
the work is a step toward earlier diagnosis of the illness 
friedreichs ataxia and toward detection of healthy people who 
unknowingly carry the gene and can pass it to their offspring the 
researchers said 
scientists hope to isolate the gene as a clue to possible 
treatments the disease now has no cure or specific treatment 
the study was reported in todays issue of the british journal 
nature by researchers at st marys hospital medical school in 
london the howard hughes medical institute at the university of 
utah school of medicine and the karolinska institute in stockholm 
sweden 
friedreichs ataxia afflicts probably 15000 to 20000 people in 
the united states but no reliable statistics are available said 
donald wood of the muscular dystrophy association which helped 
finance the research 
the lifethreatening disease causes reduced muscle coordination 
and an irregular gait the limbs may become weak and tasks that 
require good coordination such as writing may become difficult 
speech may also be impaired 
the disease appears when both copies of the friedreichs ataxia 
gene that a person inherits from his parents are defective 
genes lie along threadlike structures called chromosomes the 
new study based on 22 families with three or more affected 
siblings says the friedreichs ataxia gene lies in a particular 
portion of the chromosome scientists call number 9 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

