<TEXT>
two moslems refused to accept a 
total of 513000 in lottery winnings saying their religion bars 
them from taking money from games of chance because that would 
amount to gambling 
rathi ishak general manager of the governmentbacked social 
welfare lottery board told reporters today that a man who won a 
133000 prize in one drawing said he bought the ticket as a 
donation to charity and it would be wrong for him to accept the 
money 
earlier last year another man refused to take his prize money 
of 380000 also because it was against his islamic religious 
principles said rathi adding that that man too had bought the 
ticket for charity 
the lottery was started in 1950 by the british colonialists to 
gather funds to run homes for orphans and old people and for other 
charities he said and continued after independence in 1957 
six million tickets at about 38 cents per ticket are sold for 
each drawing which are held every three weeks in each drawing 
125 million in prizes is awarded 
