<TEXT>
the united states and japan have reached 
agreement on a pact to end or relax japanese import quotas on 
various us processed food products 
under the accord japan will end quotas on seven food categories 
by april 1 1990 and partially lift quotas to substantially 
increase access or provide compensation on four other categories 
us trade representative clayton yeutter said late wednesday 
the pact is a further example that with persistence and 
perseverance the united states can open markets abroad for our 
products 
i am pleased that we were able to finally reach an 
agreement to implement the report of gatt the general agreement on 
tariffs and trade which ruled that japans quotas were illegal 
under international trading rules he said 
this sets a precedent for other pending cases we have before 
the gatt in which the united states is denied access to foreign 
agricultural markets 
the japanese embassy said full agreement was reached wednesday 
after a final threeday round of negotiations between yeutters 
office and a delegation from tokyos ministry of agriculture and 
fisheries 
it ends a dispute spawned by a 1986 us complaint against 
quotas in 12 categories of processed foods 
after japan blocked the formation of a panel of inquiry twice a 
panel report last november found the quotas on 10 categories were 
illegal by gatt standards 
the report adopted by the gatt council on feb 2 allowed japan 
to continue its import restrictions on two categories peanuts 
and dried peas and beans if the quotas were increased in other 
areas 
yeutter said he expected last years 480 million in us 
exports to japan to double by the end of the threeyear settlement 
period with unlimited export potential throughout the next decade 
</TEXT>
