<TEXT>
here is the text of the speech delivered by 
coretta scott king at the democratic national convention 
five weeks from today on august 27 we will commemorate the 
25th anniversary of martin luther king jrs dream for america by 
marching on washington once again 
on that august afternoon in 1963 more than 250000 people from 
all walks of life assembled in the lengthened shadow of the lincoln 
memorial on that day martin luther king jr stood before the 
nation and the world and declared his dream for america 
martins dream was embraced by many americans some like medgar 
evers john and bobby kennedy and countless others already 
mentioned here this week have sacrificed and even given their lives 
in pursuit of that dream 
under martin luther kings jrs leadership the civil rights 
movement awakened the conscience of america and achieved great 
victories in the struggle for equality his accomplishments are 
much in evidence in this historic convention the state of 
mississippi for example was described by martin as sweltering 
with the heat of injustice yet in 1986 mississippi elected 
michael espy the first grandson of a former slave to the congress 
since reconstruction 
it has also sent to georgia this week a former confederate 
state a fully integrated delegation to this convention shared by 
a black man black americans have made great strides in the 
political arena as speakers of state legislatures as chairs of 
eight congressional committees and theres even a black american 
william gray sharing the congressional budget committee and this 
conventions platform committee 
and tonight i want to pause to say jesse martin would be 
proud of you and we are all proud of you by the way you have 
broadened and expanded the base of political participation in 
america so many who were formerly locked out are now locked in as 
a disciple of martin luther king jr your campaign has brought new 
hope to millions who had given up on ever participating in the 
political process 
these accomplishments serve to remind us that todays dreams can 
be tomorrows reality but we must be willing to work together to 
pray together to struggle together in the spirit of noneviolence 
to fulfill martins dream 
the leaders of this convention gov michael dukakis lloyd 
bentsen jesse jackson and jimmy carter have beautifully 
demonstrated the power of nonviolence at work in the healing and 
reconciliation that has taken place at this convention 
gov dukakis i want to commend you for conducting your campaign 
on a consistently high plane and spirit i come to this convention 
tonight to remind you that this is what the dream is all about i 
come also to remind you that for many americans the dream is still 
deferred despite the progress of the last 25 years something is 
still wrong when 32 million americans are living in poverty in the 
richest nation on the face of the earth and something is very 
wrong when nearly 13 million of them are children this is a 
national disgrace 
we cannot allow this to go unchallenged as americans let us 
take the challenge of making those whom the bible call the least 
of these victims of aids the poor and the homeless a top 
priority let us not abandon the victims of neglect 
it would be tragic a tragic mistake to attract the haves 
to any political party at the expense of the have nots we can 
feed our hungry 
we can provide decent housing for all of our citizens we can 
provide jobs skills training and day care for the poor and 
unemployed so that they can put bread on their own tables 
we can help every american who wants to work to be productive 
to do so we can end the violence of nuclear war apartheid 
racism joblessness terrorism drugs and the violence in our 
homes in our schools and in our streets if only we can find the 
will and we must 
and finally my brothers and sisters we can be proud of our 
economic prosperity and the blessings of freedom but if we want to 
be and if we want the gospel of freedom spread and human rights 
throughout the world we must lead by our moral example we can 
and we must be peacemakers i ask you my friends please do not 
forsake martins dream and i join jesse jackson in appealing to 
you to keep hope alive 
i challenge you to remember the dream 
thank you 
</TEXT>
