<TEXT>
if the democratic national convention seems more 
like a hollywood production than a political event hollywood 
producer gary smith has done his job 
shouting staccato bursts of instructions into a telephone 
headset smith is orchestrating every minute of the action from a 
control center its occupants call tech tower the top tier of the 
imposing camera stand opposite the podium 
kenneth mack is coming in lower the lights hold it hold it 
lower the podium and music 
with the singing of the national anthem safely under way the 
producer could lean back and relax for three minutes 
smith a trim man with a mustache glasses and a yellow tie 
sits before five television monitors surrounded by notebooks 
telephones and a timer that he clutches anxiously when politicians 
go into overtime at the rostrum 
his crisp directions are heard over an open line by the 
orchestra conductor the podium stage manager the teleprompter 
operator and his partner dwight hemion director of television 
coverage for the partys satellite service to stations across the 
nation 
as the convention opened wednesday at 6 pm smith was in his 
element directing preparations for a boy scout color guard 
gesticulating at his operatives on the podium scribbling notes on 
his schedule requesting frequent changes of lighting from don tyra 
sitting beside him at a console 
by 830 pm the program was nearly an hour behind byebye to 
introductions of the youngest delegate and former house speaker 
carl albert so long for the second time to a videotaped tribute to 
party secretary dorothy bush 
smith was not worried there was a 46minute recess built into 
the session but when it came officials apparently had not decided 
whether to cancel it or not there were long seconds of emptiness 
at the podium 
some music smith yelled into his headset some music 
the orchestra obliged and the officials shortly decided to go on 
with the show 
it wasnt the only time smith had to do some quick thinking 
when a delegate scheduled to introduce three governors began 
speaking into a dead microphone from her place in the indiana 
delegation smith quickly turned on a mike in front of him 
ladies and gentlemen he announced in a deep voice the 
governor of colorado roy romer 
often by gestures alone smith issued lighting instructions to 
go black or brighten up suddenly or slowly and by the subtle 
movement of tyras finger on a control the hall would fall silent 
all eyes on the podium a demonstration would explode or wane on 
cue with bright or fading lights 
nearly five hours before the california delegation clinched the 
nomination for the massachusetts governor smith was explaining to 
tyra how to dramatize the moment youll feel it in the hall 
he said well bring the lights down theyll say california and 
well bring the lights up 
tension mounted as the moment approached sneak em down 
sneak em down smith told tyra stand by ready to bring em 
up ready music not now not now as the california delegation 
started cheering its own lieutenant governor 
then the announcement california gives 235 votes to dukakis 
go music smith yelled tyra zipped up the lights the 
orchestra began a medley of its a grand old flag and the 
washington post march placards waved delegates cheered smith 
actually stood up and clapped his hands twice 
they said it looks great he exulted listening to a 
convention official on his headset i think its great but its 
nice to hear it from them turn the lights down a little bit 
keep the spotlights going 
the demonstration continued enthusiastically until smith 
realized the television networks were switching back to local 
programming is nbc gone he yelled frantically is nbc gone 
yes and into the headphone ok cut it the music stopped 
instantly and the demonstration petered out 
dick ortner of abc the host network said profits dictate the 
network decisions to cut away from convention coverage if a 
demonstration goes too far he explained they see money going 
down the tube 
</TEXT>
