a team of explorers plans to raise the worlds 
largest 19thcentury steam whaling ship from the frigid depths of 
the chukchi sea off alaska and even has visions of sailing the old 
vessel again 
the 177foot whaler orca which sank in september 1897 after it 
got wedged between two pieces of floating ice is like an 
underwater time capsule said project director dan w shirey 
we have found that the yearround belowfreezing temperatures 
of the water makes the ocean environment marine organismfree no 
other area of the world can offer such ideal preservation 
conditions for marine antiquities 
indeed the vessel once the pride of americas whaling fleet 
is believed to be so well preserved that shirey dreams of sailing 
it to a new home perhaps next to the queen mary in long beach 
calif or to the south street seaport in new york 
in this melting pot of new york the ship could find a home 
under the shadows of the lady statue of liberty herself he 
said at a news conference wednesday at the explorers club a 
private organization of professional explorers and scientists 
ninetyone years ago the orca owned by the pacific steam 
whaling co of san francisco sank sternfirst in about 100 feet 
of water off point franklin alaska the captain and crew escaped 
you couldnt have asked for a gentler shipwreck said 
shirey a former coast guard searchandrescue diver who founded 
the ocean research center of the arctic a nonprofit organization 
for preserving the regions maritime heritage it was established 
in 1985 at point barrow alaska 
on aug 6 he will lead a team of nine explorers to a base camp 
at peard bay alaska they will survey and photograph the wreck 
using small boats sonar and remotecontrolled undersea vehicles 
until about sept 30 when the ice moves back into place for the 
winter 
the 25 million phase 2 dredging beneath the 628ton vessel 
attaching large slings to its frame and lifting it with barges is 
to begin late next summer 
time is limited because a proposed offshore pipeline might 
disturb the historic wreck shirey said at the explorers club 
which is underwriting the 150000 first phase 
we found the whaling ships timbers to be wormfree and as 
