five managers at the three mile island 2 
nuclear plant have been disciplined for not doing enough to stop a 
control room supervisor from sleeping on the job the plant 
operator says 
gpu nuclear corp said wednesday it had fired an employee 
reassigned two and reprimanded two 
the action was prompted by an independent report critical of 
managements role in dealing with the sleeping allegations said 
gpu spokesman doug bedell 
following company policy the workers were not identified 
the report by former new jersey division of criminal justice 
director edwin h stier concluded that managers did not 
aggressively investigate allegations in 1986 and 1987 that the 
control room shift supervisor was sleeping on duty thus indirectly 
allowing the situation to continue 
the shift supervisor was fired nov 27 after an earlier report 
by stier found the sleeping had occurred as early as 1983 and 
continued into 1987 
the unit 2 reactor site of the nations worst commercial 
nuclear accident has been shut down since 1979 the shift 
supervisor oversees staff fireprotection systems and radiation 
monitors at the plant 
the latest report said management failed to probe the 
allegations fully accepted denials by the supervisor and 
discounted others statements resulting in inaccurate and 
distorted information being passed on to the nuclear regulatory 
commission 
there was a breakdown in communication between the operating 
crews and the gpu managers immediately above them such that the 
managers failed to learn the extent of the supervisors 
inattentiveness the report said 
nrc spokesman karl abraham said the agency had received the 
report but had not made a determination whether there were any 
regulatory violations 
bedell acknowledged that the allegations had been handled poorly 
they managers didnt get a full picture of what occurred 
the situation festered bedell said we have lessons to learn 
as far as supervisory techniques this was not handled well 
kay pickering a spokeswoman for tmi alert a citizens group 
said the report underscores continuing problems at tmi 
we feel gpu still does not have a handle on good management 
reading between the lines there are still serious problems 
she said 
