<TEXT>
a mistake that damaged a space shuttle 
booster rocket intended for a crucial test firing resulted from 
confusion during a shift change at morton thiokols plant a nasa 
official said 
the accident occurred july 9 when a worker testing one of the 
rockets three field joints inadvertently switched pressurization 
lines and damaged insulation that helps contain superhot exhaust 
gases during flight 
the damage at thiokols plant west of here delayed a testfiring 
of the rocket motor this month until late august company officials 
said 
thiokols booster was redesigned after a presidential commission 
found that a faulty joint was responsible for the jan 28 1986 
explosion that destroyed the space shuttle challenger and grounded 
the us manned space flight program 
the booster firing test is the last of five required on the 
redesigned rocket before shuttle flights can resume 
royce mitchell director of nasas shuttle rocket motor program 
said a replacement shift had come on duty just before the accident 
and the fresh workers incorrectly believed the first crew had 
checked the equipment 
that little significant piece of data was lost between the 
two crews mitchell said in a telephone interview tuesday from 
the marshall space flight center in huntsville ala 
he said the second crew would have discovered the hoses were 
improperly attached if they had checked them before the 
pressurization test one of many tests in preparation for a 
testfiring 
he said that after the accident company workers and nasa 
officials inspected the motor and found that a seal had been 
deformed when the hose sent 950 pounds per square inch of pressure 
into the joint instead of the intended 100 psi 
the joint was repaired and the rocket is being reassembled for 
the test firing 
