the soviet union and china have agreed to meet 
in beijing next month in an attempt to work out a peace settlement 
for vietnameseoccupied cambodia a us official said thursday 
if successful the talks could remove the remaining obstacle to 
a summit meeting between the worlds two biggest communist powers 
who have been at odds for some 30 years the official said 
this is the first time the two sides are holding a meeting with 
cambodia as the sole agenda item although they have been 
conducting periodic talks on the foreign ministry level since 1982 
the official said the soviets will be represented at the august 
meeting by deputy foreign minister igor rogachev and the chinese by 
foreign ministry official zhu qizhen the official said 
while neither the soviets nor the chinese have a direct role in 
the longrunning cambodia conflict both powers hold sway over 
allies who are directly involved 
secretary of state george shultz was informed of the planned 
talks during his visit to beijing last week said the official 
speaking only on condition of anonymity 
but he cautioned that the success of the cambodia meeting hinges 
on the upcoming cocktail party talks among the threeparty 
cambodian guerrilla coalition vietnamese officials and the 
vietnamappointed government in the capital of phnom penh 
