<TEXT>
president robert g mugabe of zimbabwe was 
awarded the 1988 africa prize for leadership for shepherding his 
multiracial people through independence and early statehood 
officials announced thursday 
speaking in a global teleconference from lusaka the capital of 
zambia and the united nations in new york prize jury chairman 
bradford morse described mugabe as one of the intellectual giants 
of the african continent 
president kenneth kaunda of zambia spoke about mugabe an old 
friend calling him a truly gallant freedom fighter 
mugabe and joshua nkomo led the black independence struggle in 
zimbabwe a southern african nation previously known as rhodesia 
mugabe fought prime minister ian smiths whiteruled government 
which broke away from britain with a unilateral declaration of 
independence in 1965 
a britishmediated accord ushered in a ceasefire and elections 
that established black majority rule in 1979 mugabe became prime 
minister in 1980 and invited the white minority to join in national 
reconstruction he became president in 1987 
morse singled out mugabes approach of reconciliation with the 
white minority including smith and with nkomo who until this 
year led a rival political party such moves provide examples of 
mugabes visionary approach to political leadership morse said 
under mugabe black peasant farmers increased their crop 
revenues tenfold since 1980 according to morse who coordinated 
famine relief as former administator of the un development 
program at the same time the black farmers increased their share 
of the nations farm production from 10 percent to 64 percent 
morse said peasant farmers in zimbabwe now receive 18 times more 
farms loans than they did in 1979 
the award ceremony is scheduled for sept 15 in new york the 
prize consists of 100000 to be used to promote the winners work 
on behalf of the people of africa and a sculpture by artist 
takenobu igarashi 
the africa prize for leadership award was instituted two years 
ago by the new yorkbased nonprofit organization the hunger 
project about 54 million volunteers and staff in 152 nations are 
helping the hunger project try to abolish hunger worldwide 
organizers said 
in the first award ceremony last year president abdou diouf of 
senegal and professor thomas r odhiambo of kenya a specialist in 
insect studies received prizes 
</TEXT>
