<TEXT>
cartoonist and magazine editor mark boxer whose 
barbed depictions of the fads and foibles of middleclass 
trendsetters entertained britain for 20 years has died his 
family announced thursday he was 57 
boxer died wednesday of a brain tumor at his home in london 
after a fivemonth illness 
from 1968 until this year boxers cartoons appeared in a 
variety of newspapers and magazines including the times of london 
the guardian the observer the daily telegraph the listener and 
the new statesman 
drawing under the name marc he chose as targets people in 
television newspapers advertising and publishing real estate 
agents interior designers and a host of other upwardly mobile 
professionals his cartoons always were the width of a single 
newspaper column 
he invented the north london world of tv producers 
reviewers and dons university academics not averse to publicity 
and the beau monde the daily telegraph said he had no 
affection for the characters he created his couple simon and 
joanna stringalong poisoned life 
joanna was cowardly and had no friends simon went in 
for every trendy cause and dropped each when it was no longer 
fashionable all they wanted was to be in with those who mattered 
in the media world 
the times wrote marc drew the trendies and the 
publishers the hampstead in north london intellectuals 
lecturers teachers and politicians the miniskirted and student 
rebels he was hawkeyed to spot a trend 
in 1975 when wealthy arabs were buying up expensive london real 
estate boxer depicted a real estate agent telling his secretary 
change the line about facing south to facing east 
britons like homes facing south in order to catch the sun but 
arabs and other moslems face east to mecca to pray three times a 
day 
boxer was born may 19 1931 and his father was an army colonel 
he went to cambridge university but was suspended for publishing a 
poem considered blasphemous as a stunt he left in a hearse 
accompanied by friends as mourners 
he returned at the end of the brief suspension but student life 
bored him and he left without a degree 
after a short stint with the sunday express newspaper he joined 
the ambassador a fashion export magazine and began drawing for 
the fashion and society magazine tatler 
in 1957 he became art editor at another fashion and society 
magazine queen and from 196265 edited the magazine section of 
the sunday times 
employing big names like painter david hockney and photographer 
lord snowdon boxer made the sunday times magazine into a major 
publishing success 
he worked for a variety of other magazines over the years and 
became editor in chief of vogue another top fashion and society 
magazine last year 
his first marriage to food writer lady arabella stuart third 
daughter of the 18th earl of moray ended in divorce in 1982 they 
had a son and a daughter 
he then married anna ford one of britains leading tv 
announcers who survives him they had two daughters 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

