<TEXT>
the likely source of pollution that 
has plagued four new jersey seashore communities since last week is 
the asbury park sewage treatment plant health officials said 
thursday 
beaches in asbury park ocean grove bradley beach and 
avonbythesea were closed again thursday after tests showed high 
levels of coliform or fecal bacteria in the ocean 
the first beach closings occurred june 13 and monmouth county 
health officials initially pointed to polluted sylvan lake which 
empties into the ocean but health officials realized the lake 
would not be the source of balls of grease that had washed ashore 
such pollution is commonly associated with sewerage plants 
the county received state department of environmental protection 
assistance and investigators checked all local sewerage plants and 
pumping stations chlorinated nearby lakes and looked at local 
rivers 
meantime the bacteria slowly dissipated and beaches reopened 
by wednesday all but four blocks in asbury park were reopened to 
swimmers said myron lavake environmental program administrator 
for the monmouth county health department 
then on wednesday night as part of their investigation county 
and state health officials monitored operations at the sewage 
treatment plants in asbury park and neptune 
the team discovered the asbury park plant was inefficiently 
operating during the night monmouth county spokesman paul ridner 
said during the day it seemed to be fine 
apparently tides washed away most of the pollutants by the time 
health officials took tests each morning prompting beaches to 
slowly reopen said lester jargowsky monmouth county health 
officer 
the coliform sometimes reached more than eight times the state 
standard which is 200 colonies per 100 milliliters of water he 
said 
officials in the four affected seashore communities meanwhile 
lamented the loss of business since the pollution closings began 
business has been absolutely brutal in ocean grove this past 
week said beach manager august g stoll 
</TEXT>
