<TEXT>
iraq renewed its demand for direct peace 
negotiations with iran and said thursday it has not yet decided 
whether to receive a un team assigned to work out details of a 
truce in the 8yearold war 
the request of the secretarygeneral to dispatch the mission 
is under discussion in baghdad iraqs ambassador ismat t 
kittani told a news conference 
iran said monday it would accept a yearold security council 
ceasefire resolution it has agreed to receive the eightman un 
military team due in tehran on sunday but rejected iraqs demand 
that the two governments negotiate directly with each other 
mohammad jaafar mahallati the iranian ambassador criticized 
iraqs demand for direct talks and its other new proposals as 
extraneous elements which will only complicate the whole thing 
and delay a truce 
he told reporters iraq wants to prolong the war gain some 
more territory and leverage and reinforce their aggressive 
policies 
members of the 15nation security council began informal 
consultations on the situation they also were discussing problems 
with the technical team and the new iraqi demands 
un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar later told 
reporters that he was reflecting very carefully on the letter 
from iraqi foreign minister tariq aziz who urged immediate and 
direct consultations with iran in new york the un chief also 
said he was considering inviting both foreign ministers to un 
headquarters in new york but had not made a decision 
aliakbar velayati the iranian foreign minister sent a letter 
to perez de cuellar on thursday saying his government is fully 
prepared to receive and cooperate with the technical mission on 
details of a ceasefire 
his letter which diplomats made available to the associated 
press said iran also is prepared to show military restraint 
iraq said soon after the council passed resolution 598 on july 
20 1987 that it would accept the plan if iran did but the 
iranians said no truce could take effect until iraq was branded the 
aggressor in the war 
now iran favors an immediate ceasefire and iraq is hesitant 
president saddam husseins government says it suspects iran of 
playing for time to rebuild its war machine 
perez de cuellar is assembling a second un team to visit the 
region this weekend and determine the situation of prisoners of war 
the security councils resolution 598 calls for a ceasefire to 
be followed by withdrawal of military forces to recognized borders 
prisoner exchange peace negotiations and an investigation of which 
side started the war iraq invaded iran in september 1980 after 
several border skirmishes 
kittani the iraqi ambassador said after his fourth meeting in 
two days with perez de cuellar we think the first step should be 
facetoface discussions with iran under the auspices of the 
secretarygeneral 
in response to questions perez de cuellar told reporters he was 
not yet disappointed with progress in implementing a truce and did 
not blame either side 
asked whether iraqs insistence on direct talks might block or 
delay the technical mission perez de cuella said no they the 
iraqis only want clarifications which i will give to them 
the military team of officers from the un truce supervisory 
organization is to leave friday or saturday from vienna or 
jerusalem 
iraq has said it was suspicious of irans abrupt acceptance of 
the security council plan after rejecting it for a year 
kittani said thursday that the iranian ambassadors comments 
added to our legitimate suspiciouns as mr mahallati dismissed 
our proposals as irrelevant 
he wants an immediate ceasefire but there is no commitement 
from himself or his government to even talk to iraq 
the iraqi envoy also emphasized the importance of dredging the 
shattalarab waterway which forms the southern border between the 
two countries and is iraqs only outlet to the sea 
rival claims to the shattalarab were a major cause of the war 
kittani said thursday the issue should be discussed in direct 
talks and that iraqi access to the waterway is essential to peace 
in the region he declined to answer questions about whether 
acceptance of the ceasefire team was linked to iraqs demand for 
direct negotiations 
middle east diplomats said privately that iraq was annoyed by 
perez de cuellars handling of his announcement of the technical 
teams mission they said he consulted mahallati but did not wait 
for official iraqi acceptance 
