<TEXT>
a plan to dump american household garbage in 
britain has been well dumped 
nick baig the british businessman who devised the scheme said 
thursday that an application for permission to import refuse from 
the eastern united states to northwest england has been withdrawn 
because of impossible conditions set by the government 
critics of the idea say the american garbage could have brought 
new diseases into the country and taken up dumping space needed by 
britain so when parliament was told wednesday night that the deal 
was off there was general relief 
it is unacceptable that the northwest should be made the 
worlds dust bin said winston churchill grandson of the wartime 
leader and lawmaker for the area 
baig however accuses the british of getting too emotional 
about what he believes was a beautifully simple idea to extract 
gold from them thar trash cans 
in an interview he explained that his british company power 
water and waste was negotiating with american municipalities for 
ships to pick up garbage in new york boston and philadelphia and 
take it across the atlantic to be dumped on a 390acre landfill 
site in merseyside greater liverpool 
the americans he said would pay him 50 for each ton of 
garbage removed and he would pay the british authorities 12 per 
ton dumped at this end 
baig said he would have relieved the americans of 12 million 
tons a year over five years 
but things could never be that simple 
when baig eyed abandoned tin mines in cornwall the southwest 
peninsula of england as potential garbage sites the opposition 
was so fierce that he had to shift his sights northward the 
manchester ship canal co was interested and applied for a license 
to have the imported garbage dumped at its merseyside landfill 
but faced with an influx of sticky beer cans nonbiodegradable 
cereal boxes and halfeaten hamburgers the government proved less 
than enthusiastic 
our opinion was that it was a large volume of waste which 
could have serious implications for plant and animal health 
because it could carry viruses from outside the country said 
brendan clark an environment department spokesman 
the ministry of agriculture told the importers they would need a 
sanitation license 
that is an impossibility because how can anybody inspect half 
a million dust bins said baig the law was designed for the 
import of fresh meat and products in our plan none of the rubbish 
would enter the food chain of beast bird plant or man 
