golovin was one of five soviet soldiers captured and held by 
afghan rebels then spirited away by canadian officials on a secret 
mission in november 1986 
he was working parttime at a meat processing plant in 
kitchener ontario but he complained that he never felt at home in 
canada 
efforts to bring the soviet deserters to canada began in july 
1984 when toronto lawyer serge jusyp met with several of them in 
afghanistan jusyp who was acting on behalf of the holy trinity 
russian orthodox church in toronto persuaded rebel leaders to 
release the men if canada offered asylum my comrades staying in 
canada should know that nothing has happened to me after my return 
home tass quoted golovin as saying i believe that fear of a 
possible punishment keeps them there 
he said the deserters had been warned by their canadian contacts 
that they would face reprisals if they returned to the soviet union 
the former soldier said those fears have been alleviated by 
soviet prosecutorgeneral alexander sukharevs declaration of 
amnesty for soldiers who had been unable to suffer any longer 
tortures and privations of captivity and committed wrongdoings to 
the detriment of the ussr 
golovin told reporters before leaving canada that he wanted to 
return to where russian was spoken and to see his sister and ailing 
mother he planned to find work as an electrician in his home town 
of ulyanovsk a city on the volga river 500 miles east of moscow 
the soviets are now withdrawing their more than 110000 troops 
from afghanistan 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

