schlumberger ltd a new yorkbased oil services concern on 
thursday reported its secondquarter earnings increased nearly 
fivefold due in part to firmer prices for the companys services 
market gains and the sale of a business unit 
net income for the quarter ended june 30 totaled 144 million 
or 53 cents a share up from 302 million or 11 cents a share in 
the yearago period revenue rose 22 percent to 135 billion from 
111 billion in the second quarter of 1987 
the figures include a 35 million gain from the sale of the 
companys electricity control and transformers division 
schlumberger chairman euan baird said in a statement the 
companys worldwide oilfield services operations grew 20 percent 
boosted by firmer prices and market gains 
he said that so far the price of oil and gas has had little 
effect on oil company activity but cautioned that if present 
price levels continue to erode the strength of the normal second 
half surge in rig activity in north america will be adversely 
affected 
for the year to date schlumberger reported net income of 245 
million or 90 cents a share compared to 35 million or 13 cents 
a share in the first six months of 1987 revenue totaled 265 
billion up from 221 billion in the yearago period 
schlumberger performs specialized service to oil drillers and 
producers in addition to making equipment and machinery 
