general motors corp reported thursday that its 
profit rose strongly in the second quarter as overseas operations 
had a recordbreaking performance and sales picked up in north 
america 
financial analysts said the gains in domestic sales should cheer 
the worlds largest automaker which has seen its us market share 
eroded in recent years 
gm had aftertax earnings of 15 billion or 452 a share in 
the apriljune period the companys best quarterly profit in four 
years that was up 53 percent from a net of 9803 million or 
280 a share in the same quarter of 1987 but gm noted the gain 
would have been about 28 percent if an accounting change had been 
made retroactive to the first half of last year 
gm said its profit for the 1987 period would have been 117 
billion if the change had been in effect 
secondquarter revenue rose 12 percent to 299 billion from 
267 billion surpassing gms previous quarterly sales record of 
276 billion set in 1986 
general motors improved profitability reflects its increasing 
competitive north american automotive operations both in terms of 
strengthening market position and improving operating efficiency 
gm chairman roger smith and president robert stempel said in a 
joint statement 
further overseas earnings in 1988 are exceeding the record 
levels achieved in 1987 they said 
for the first six months of 1988 gm had a profit of 26 
billion or 763 a share on revenue of 563 billion that was up 
133 percent from the 229 billion or 665 a share it would 
have earned on revenue of 528 billion a year ago if the 
accounting change had been in effect 
gm slowed the rate of depreciation of plants tools and 
equipment beginning in the third quarter of 1987 to match 
depreciation schedules used by its auto industry competition 
