<TEXT>
west publishing co and mead data central 
inc have settled their court battle for control of the 
computerassisted legal research marketplace the two companies 
announced thursday 
west attorney vance k opperman said both parties finally came 
to the realization that the diversion of time and money would be 
better spent focused on the market 
two federal judges helped settle the three lawsuits between the 
competitors which dominate a rapidly growing market that generates 
more than 200 million in annual sales 
both companies had sued and countersued in federal courts in 
minnesota and ohio accusing each other of copyright and 
restraintoftrade violations in connection with wests westlaw 
computerized legal research service and meads competing lexis 
service 
the settlement was reached late wednesday said dorothy molstad 
director of public relations for st paulbased west a major 
lawbook publisher 
under terms of the settlement mdc will pay west license fees 
for the use of the case report arrangements from wests copyright 
national reporter system publications on mdcs lexis system 
according to the statement 
wests national reporter system publishes judicial opinions from 
every state and federal court westlaw already includes case 
arrangements from that system 
mdc a subsidiary of mead corp a paper products manufacturer 
based in dayton ohio also will be granted a license to add wests 
compilations of various state statutes to lexis the statement said 
opperman said he thinks the two companies decided to stop 
spending their resources in the courtroom and instead fight it out 
in the market 
i think both companies feel that their business is in the 
marketplace their business is not in the courtrooms and they 
would like to return and focus all their resources on what they do 
best which is serve their customers and develop their products 
he said 
the two sides had been negotiating for the last 2 months 
opperman said 
michael winter director of communications for mdc said the 
company wanted to get the service to its customers as soon as 
possible 
this was an opportunity for us to get for our customers what 
we need through negotiations instead of litigation winter said 
settlement discussions took place in the chambers of us 
district judge james m rosenbaum in minneapolis the statement 
said 
as a result of the settlement rosenbaum and us district judge 
walter h rice of dayton have each dismissed the lawsuits pending 
before them with prejudice meaning they cannot be brought again 
the statement said 
